05324nam a22006975i 9780801455285DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20152015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808014552857 a10.7591/97808014552852doi  a(DE-B1597)496533  a(OCoLC)1041996693  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aBX4700.T4bB53 2014 7aHIS0450002bisacsh04a282/.463591 aBilinkoff, Jodi, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Avila of Saint Teresa :bReligious Reform in a Sixteenth-Century City /cJodi Bilinkoff.  aWith a New Introduction 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (264 p.) :b5 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tMaps and Illustrations -- tPreface -- tIntroduction to the 2014 Edition -- tAdditional Bibliographic Sources -- tAbbreviations -- t1. The City Of Saint Teresa -- t2. Aristocratic Dominance and Monastic Foundation, 1480-1520 -- t3. Public Works, Private Goals, 1520-1540 -- t4. Toward a New Definition of Reform, 1540-1570 -- t5. Saint Teresa Of Jesus and Carmelite Reform, 1560-1580 -- t6. Avila after Saint Teresa, 1580–1620 -- tEpilogue -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Avila of Saint Teresa provides both a fascinating account of social and religious change in one important Castilian city and a historical analysis of the life and work of the religious mystic Saint Teresa of Jesus. Jodi Bilinkoff's rich socioeconomic history of sixteenth-century Avila illuminates the conditions that helped to shape the religious reforms for which the city's most famous citizen is celebrated.Bilinkoff takes as her subject the period during which Avila became a center of intense religious activity and the home of a number of influential mystics and religious reformers. During this time, she notes, urban expansion and increased economic opportunity fostered the social and political aspirations of a new "middle class" of merchants, professionals, and minor clerics. This group supported the creation of religious institutions that fostered such values as individual spiritual revitalization, religious poverty, and apostolic service to the urban community. According to Bilinkoff, these reform movements provided an alternative to the traditional, dynastic style of spirituality expressed by the ruling elite, and profoundly influenced Saint Teresa in her renewal of Carmelite monastic life.A focal point of the book is the controversy surrounding Teresa's foundation of a new convent in August 1562. Seeking to discover why people in Avila strenuously opposed this ostensibly innocent act and to reveal what distinguished Teresa's convent from the many others in the city, Bilinkoff offers a detailed examination of the social meaning of religious institutions in Avila. Historians of early modern Europe, especially those concerned with the history of religious culture, urban history, and women's history, specialists in religious studies, and other readers interested in the life of Saint Teresa or in the history of Catholicism will welcome The Avila of Saint Teresa.First published by Cornell University Press in 1989, this new edition of The Avila of Saint Teresa includes a new introduction in which the author provides an overview of the scholarship that has proliferated and evolved over the past 25 years on topics covered in her book. This new edition also include an updated bibliography of works published since 1989 that address topics and themes discussed in her book.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aChristian saintszSpainzAvilavBiography. 4aEurope. 4aHistory. 4aReligious Studies. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Spain & Portugal.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080145528540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801455285423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801455285/original  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK